{"title_page": "Gary Fildes", "text_new": "{{Orphan|date=November 2019}}\n\n'''Gary Fildes''' (born 27 September 1965) is an amateur  astronomer.\n\n== Early life and education ==\nFildes was born in Sunderland in 1965. Growing up in Grindon, a council estate on the outskirts of Sunderland, he left school at the age of sixteen to work as a bricklayer.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.livingnorth.com/northeast/people-places/star-man-gary-fildes|title=Star Man: Gary Fildes {{!}} Living North|website=www.livingnorth.com|access-date=2019-03-24}}</ref> Not formally trained in astronomy or academia, in 2012 Fildes was given an honorary master's degree from Durham University.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/university.calendar/volumei/honorary_degrees/#MA|title=University Calendar : Honorary Degrees - Durham University|website=www.dur.ac.uk|access-date=2019-03-24}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\n\n=== Early career and Sunderland Astronomical Society ===\nFildes worked as a bricklayer in the North East for 25 years. In the late 1990s he joined the Sunderland Astronomical Society and eventually started hosting [[Kielder Forest Star Camp]]s in the [[Kielder Forest]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thejournal.co.uk/north-east-analysis/analysis-news/how-former-brickie-gary-fildes-8030984|title=How former brickie Gary Fildes reached for the stars - The Journal|last=Kelly|first=Mike|website=www.thejournal.co.uk|language=en|access-date=2019-03-24}}</ref>\n\n=== Kielder Observatory ===\nWhile running star camps and other astronomy events, Fildes was the lead contributor and driving force in the effort to build an observatory. An open competition ran through the [[Royal Institute of British Architects]], eventually raising \u00a3450,000 to construct the observatory. [[Kielder Observatory]] was officially opened on 25 April 2008 by [[Arnold Wolfendale|Sir Arnold Wolfendale]], 14th [[Astronomer Royal]]. On 9 December 2013, a 579 square mile (1,500 km<sup>2</sup>) area, jointly led by Northumberland National Park Authority, Kielder Water and Forest Park Development Trust and Kielder Observatory Astronomical Society, gained Gold Tier Dark Sky Park status from the [[International Dark-Sky Association]], becoming the largest area of protected night sky in Europe.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-tyne-25260186|title=Northumberland wins dark-sky status|date=2013-12-09|access-date=2019-03-24|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n=== After Kielder ===\nFildes departed Kielder Observatory in February 2019.{{citation needed|date=April 2019}}\n\n== Awards and honours ==\n\n* Honorary MSc, Durham University, 2012<ref name=\":0\" />\n* Honorary Fellowship, Sunderland University, 2017<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sunderland.ac.uk/more/news/story/gary-reaches-for-the-stars-208|title=Gary reaches for the stars|date=2017-07-13|website=University of Sunderland|language=en|access-date=2019-03-24}}</ref>\n\n== Works ==\n\n=== Non-fiction ===\n[https://www.penguin.co.uk/books/1110978/an-astronomer-s-tale/9781784754389.html An Astronomer's Tale] (2016)\n\n=== Film and Media ===\n[http://www.inhousefilms.com/work/searching-for-light/ Searching for Light documentary] (2016)\n\n[http://www.inhousefilms.com/work/apollo-tribute/ The Apollo Tribute] (2015)\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fildes, Gary}}\n[[Category:1965 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:British bricklayers]]\n[[Category:British astronomers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Orphan|date=November 2019}}\n\n'''Gary Fildes''' (born 27 September 1965) is an amateur  astronomer.\n\n== Early life and education ==\nFildes was born in Sunderland in 1965. Growing up in Grindon, a council estate on the outskirts of Sunderland, he left school at the age of sixteen to work as a bricklayer.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.livingnorth.com/northeast/people-places/star-man-gary-fildes|title=Star Man: Gary Fildes {{!}} Living North|website=www.livingnorth.com|access-date=2019-03-24}}</ref> Not formally trained in astronomy or academia, in 2012 Fildes was given an honorary master's degree from Durham University.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/university.calendar/volumei/honorary_degrees/#MA|title=University Calendar : Honorary Degrees - Durham University|website=www.dur.ac.uk|access-date=2019-03-24}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\n\n=== Early career and Sunderland Astronomical Society ===\nFildes worked as a bricklayer in the North East for 25 years. In the late 1990s he joined the Sunderland Astronomical Society and eventually started hosting [[Kielder Forest Star Camp]]s in the [[Kielder Forest]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thejournal.co.uk/north-east-analysis/analysis-news/how-former-brickie-gary-fildes-8030984|title=How former brickie Gary Fildes reached for the stars - The Journal|last=Kelly|first=Mike|website=www.thejournal.co.uk|language=en|access-date=2019-03-24}}</ref>\n\n=== Kielder Observatory ===\nWhile running star camps and other astronomy events, Fildes assisted  in the effort to build an observatory. An open competition ran through the [[Royal Institute of British Architects]], eventually raising \u00a3450,000 to construct the observatory. [[Kielder Observatory]] was officially opened on 25 April 2008 by [[Arnold Wolfendale|Sir Arnold Wolfendale]], 14th [[Astronomer Royal]]. On 9 December 2013, a 579 square mile (1,500 km<sup>2</sup>) area, jointly led by Northumberland National Park Authority, Kielder Water and Forest Park Development Trust and Kielder Observatory Astronomical Society, gained Gold Tier Dark Sky Park status from the [[International Dark-Sky Association]], becoming the largest area of protected night sky in Europe.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-tyne-25260186|title=Northumberland wins dark-sky status|date=2013-12-09|access-date=2019-03-24|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n=== After Kielder ===\nFildes departed Kielder Observatory in February 2019.{{citation needed|date=April 2019}}\n\n== Awards and honours ==\n\n* Honorary MSc, Durham University, 2012<ref name=\":0\" />\n* Honorary Fellowship, Sunderland University, 2017<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sunderland.ac.uk/more/news/story/gary-reaches-for-the-stars-208|title=Gary reaches for the stars|date=2017-07-13|website=University of Sunderland|language=en|access-date=2019-03-24}}</ref>\n\n== Works ==\n\n=== Non-fiction ===\n[https://www.penguin.co.uk/books/1110978/an-astronomer-s-tale/9781784754389.html An Astronomer's Tale] (2016)\n\n=== Film and Media ===\n[http://www.inhousefilms.com/work/searching-for-light/ Searching for Light documentary] (2016)\n\n[http://www.inhousefilms.com/work/apollo-tribute/ The Apollo Tribute] (2015)\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fildes, Gary}}\n[[Category:1965 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:British bricklayers]]\n[[Category:British astronomers]]\n", "name_user": "Aristachus", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gary_Fildes"}
